{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01U4jk9FvcbijCotvGBYmKc1","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Story 19.2: Epic Flow Execution\n2\t\n3\tStatus: ready-for-dev\n4\t\n5\t<!-- Note: Validation is optional. Run validate-create-story for quality check before dev-story. -->\n6\t\n7\t## Story\n8\t\n9\tAs a developer,\n10\tI want `epic_flow` tasks to execute in sequence when an epic completes,\n11\tso that retro, merge, and validate happen automatically.\n12\t\n13\t## Acceptance Criteria\n14\t\n15\t1. **Given** a new `src/lib/epic-flow-executor.ts` module, **when** imported, **then** it exports `executeEpicFlow(config: EpicFlowConfig): Promise<EpicFlowResult>` and `EpicFlowConfig`, `EpicFlowResult`, `EpicFlowStepResult` types. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n16\t\n17\t2. **Given** an epic that reaches `completing` state (all stories done), **when** `executeEpicFlow` is called with `epicFlow: ['retro', 'merge', 'validate']`, **then** it executes `retro` first, then `merge`, then `validate` — strictly in sequence, never in parallel. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n18\t\n19\t3. **Given** the `retro` step in epic_flow, **when** executed, **then** it reads telemetry data for this epic via `readTelemetryForEpic(epicId, projectDir)` from `telemetry-writer.ts` and dispatches the analyst agent with the telemetry entries as context. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n20\t\n21\t4. **Given** the `merge` step in epic_flow, **when** executed, **then** it calls `worktreeManager.mergeWorktree(epicId, mergeStrategy, testCommand, onConflict)` — this is a built-in engine-handled step (no LLM agent dispatch). <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n22\t\n23\t5. **Given** the `validate` step in epic_flow, **when** executed, **then** it runs the test suite on the merged result via `validateMerge()` from `cross-worktree-validator.ts` — this is a built-in engine-handled step (no LLM agent dispatch). <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n24\t\n25\t6. **Given** each epic_flow step completes, **when** the next step starts, **then** epic state transitions occur: `completing → merging` (before merge), `merging → validating` (before validate), `validating → done` (after validate passes) — via `transitionEpicState()` from `epic-completion.ts`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n26\t\n27\t7. **Given** any epic_flow step fails (throws or returns failure), **when** the executor processes the failure, **then** all subsequent steps are skipped and the epic state is transitioned to `failed` via `transitionEpicState()`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n28\t\n29\t8. **Given** `executeEpicFlow` completes (success or failure), **when** the result is returned, **then** `EpicFlowResult` includes: `success: boolean`, `epicId: string`, `stepsCompleted: string[]`, `stepResults: EpicFlowStepResult[]`, `failedStep: string | null`, `error: string | null`, `durationMs: number`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n30\t\n31\t9. **Given** the `EpicFlowConfig` type, **when** inspected, **then** it includes: `epicId: string`, `epicFlow: string[]` (task names from workflow), `worktreeManager: WorktreeManager`, `mergeStrategy: MergeStrategy`, `testCommand: string`, `projectDir: string`, and optional `dispatchRetro?: (epicId: string, telemetry: TelemetryEntry[]) => Promise<void>` callback for the retro agent dispatch. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n32\t\n33\t10. **Given** the lane pool completes an epic (all stories done), **when** the epic flow executor runs, **then** it frees the lane after the epic flow completes (success or failure) so the next pending epic can be scheduled. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n34\t\n35\t11. **Given** an `epicFlow` array that is empty (`[]`), **when** `executeEpicFlow` is called, **then** it returns immediately with `success: true`, `stepsCompleted: []`, and transitions the epic directly to `done`. <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n36\t\n37\t12. **Given** the `merge` step succeeds, **when** the worktree is no longer needed, **then** `worktreeManager.cleanupWorktree(epicId)` is called to remove the worktree and delete the branch — the cleanup happens inside `mergeWorktree()` itself (already implemented in 18-1). <!-- verification: test-provable -->\n38\t\n39\t## Tasks / Subtasks\n40\t\n41\t- [ ] Task 1: Create `src/lib/epic-flow-executor.ts` (AC: #1, #8, #9)\n42\t  - [ ] Define `EpicFlowConfig` interface with all required fields\n43\t  - [ ] Define `EpicFlowStepResult` interface: `{ step: string, success: boolean, durationMs: number, error?: string }`\n44\t  - [ ] Define `EpicFlowResult` interface with all result fields\n45\t  - [ ] Define `EpicFlowError` class extending `Error`\n46\t  - [ ] Export all types and the main `executeEpicFlow` function\n47\t\n48\t- [ ] Task 2: Implement step-to-state mapping (AC: #6)\n49\t  - [ ] Map epic_flow step names to epic state transitions: `merge → merging`, `validate → validating`\n50\t  - [ ] After all steps succeed, transition to `done`\n51\t  - [ ] Use `transitionEpicState()` from `epic-completion.ts` for all transitions\n52\t  - [ ] Handle the case where a step name has no explicit state mapping (keep current state)\n53\t\n54\t- [ ] Task 3: Implement `retro` step handler (AC: #3)\n55\t  - [ ] Read telemetry via `readTelemetryForEpic(epicId, projectDir)`\n56\t  - [ ] If `dispatchRetro` callback is provided, call it with epicId and telemetry entries\n57\t  - [ ] If no callback, log that retro was skipped (no analyst agent configured)\n58\t  - [ ] Return step result with success/failure\n59\t\n60\t- [ ] Task 4: Implement `merge` step handler (AC: #4, #12)\n61\t  - [ ] Call `worktreeManager.mergeWorktree(epicId, mergeStrategy, testCommand, onConflict)`\n62\t  - [ ] Convert `MergeResult` to step result\n63\t  - [ ] `mergeWorktree` already handles worktree cleanup on success (AC #12)\n64\t\n65\t- [ ] Task 5: Implement `validate` step handler (AC: #5)\n66\t  - [ ] Call `validateMerge({ testCommand, cwd: projectDir, epicId, writeTelemetry: true })`\n67\t  - [ ] Convert `ValidationResult` to step result\n68\t\n69\t- [ ] Task 6: Implement `executeEpicFlow` orchestrator (AC: #2, #6, #7, #10, #11)\n70\t  - [ ] Accept `EpicFlowConfig`, return `Promise<EpicFlowResult>`\n71\t  - [ ] Handle empty `epicFlow` array — return success immediately, transition to `done`\n72\t  - [ ] Iterate over `epicFlow` steps sequentially\n73\t  - [ ] Before each built-in step (merge, validate), transition epic state\n74\t  - [ ] On step failure, transition to `failed`, skip remaining steps\n75\t  - [ ] After all steps succeed, transition to `done`\n76\t  - [ ] Record step results and durations\n77\t  - [ ] Return comprehensive `EpicFlowResult`\n78\t\n79\t- [ ] Task 7: Write unit tests for `src/lib/__tests__/epic-flow-executor.test.ts` (AC: #1-#12)\n80\t  - [ ] Test: `executeEpicFlow` exports the expected function and types\n81\t  - [ ] Test: steps execute in sequence (retro → merge → validate)\n82\t  - [ ] Test: `retro` step reads telemetry and dispatches callback\n83\t  - [ ] Test: `merge` step calls `worktreeManager.mergeWorktree` with correct args\n84\t  - [ ] Test: `validate` step calls `validateMerge` with correct args\n85\t  - [ ] Test: state transitions occur at each step boundary\n86\t  - [ ] Test: step failure skips remaining steps and transitions to `failed`\n87\t  - [ ] Test: `EpicFlowResult` has all expected fields\n88\t  - [ ] Test: `EpicFlowConfig` accepts all required fields\n89\t  - [ ] Test: lane is freed after completion (result returned, no hanging promise)\n90\t  - [ ] Test: empty `epicFlow` returns success and transitions to `done`\n91\t  - [ ] Test: worktree cleanup happens via `mergeWorktree` (not separately)\n92\t\n93\t## Dev Notes\n94\t\n95\t### Architecture Constraints\n96\t\n97\t- **Architecture Decision 6** (architecture-parallel-execution.md): Epic completion detection triggers epic_flow. The multi-step completion state (`completing → merging → validating → done`) is driven by this module.\n98\t- **Architecture Decision 4** (architecture-parallel-execution.md): `merge` and `validate` are built-in engine-handled steps — they do NOT dispatch an LLM agent. The `retro` step dispatches the analyst agent.\n99\t- **Hierarchical Flow Model**: The `epicFlow` step names come from `HierarchicalFlow.epicFlow` (resolved by `hierarchical-flow.ts`). Built-in steps are listed in `BUILTIN_EPIC_FLOW_TASKS`.\n100\t\n101\t### What This Story Actually Does\n102\t\n103\tThis story creates the **epic flow executor** — the orchestrator that runs `epic_flow` tasks when an epic completes. It:\n104\t\n105\t1. **Executes** `retro`, `merge`, `validate` steps in strict sequence\n106\t2. **Transitions** epic state at each step boundary via `transitionEpicState()`\n107\t3. **Delegates** to existing modules: `telemetry-writer.ts` (retro data), `worktree-manager.ts` (merge), `cross-worktree-validator.ts` (validate)\n108\t4. **Handles** failure by skipping remaining steps and marking epic as `failed`\n109\t\n110\tThis module is the **wiring layer** between:\n111\t- `epic-completion.ts` (19-1) — detects when to trigger\n112\t- `worktree-manager.ts` (17-1 / 18-1) — handles merge mechanics\n113\t- `cross-worktree-validator.ts` (18-3) — handles test validation\n114\t- `telemetry-writer.ts` (16-3) — provides retro data\n115\t- `lane-pool.ts` (17-2) — provides the execution context\n116\t\n117\t### Key Files to Create\n118\t\n119\t| File | Why |\n120\t|------|-----|\n121\t| `src/lib/epic-flow-executor.ts` | New module — epic flow orchestrator |\n122\t| `src/lib/__tests__/epic-flow-executor.test.ts` | Tests for all orchestration and wiring logic |\n123\t\n124\t### Key Files to Read (Do Not Modify)\n125\t\n126\t| File | Why |\n127\t|------|-----|\n128\t| `src/lib/epic-completion.ts` | `transitionEpicState()`, `EpicLifecycleStatus`, `EpicCompletionError` — state machine transitions |\n129\t| `src/lib/worktree-manager.ts` | `WorktreeManager.mergeWorktree()`, `MergeResult`, `MergeStrategy`, `OnConflictCallback` — merge mechanics |\n130\t| `src/lib/cross-worktree-validator.ts` | `validateMerge()`, `ValidationResult` — post-merge test validation |\n131\t| `src/lib/telemetry-writer.ts` | `readTelemetryForEpic()`, `TelemetryEntry` — retro data source |\n132\t| `src/lib/lane-pool.ts` | `LanePool`, `EpicDescriptor`, `EpicResult` — execution context |\n133\t| `src/lib/hierarchical-flow.ts` | `HierarchicalFlow`, `ExecutionConfig`, `BUILTIN_EPIC_FLOW_TASKS` — flow structure |\n134\t| `src/types/state.ts` | `SprintState`, `EpicState` — state types |\n135\t| `src/lib/null-task-registry.ts` | `NullTaskHandler`, `TaskContext` — null task pattern (merge/validate follow this pattern) |\n136\t\n137\t### Implementation Patterns\n138\t\n139\t**Epic flow executor (sequential step execution):**\n140\t```typescript\n141\texport async function executeEpicFlow(config: EpicFlowConfig): Promise<EpicFlowResult> {\n142\t  const start = Date.now();\n143\t  let state = config.initialState;\n144\t  const stepResults: EpicFlowStepResult[] = [];\n145\t  const stepsCompleted: string[] = [];\n146\t\n147\t  if (config.epicFlow.length === 0) {\n148\t    state = transitionEpicState(state, config.epicId, 'done');\n149\t    config.onStateChange?.(state);\n150\t    return { success: true, epicId: config.epicId, stepsCompleted: [], stepResults: [], failedStep: null, error: null, durationMs: Date.now() - start };\n151\t  }\n152\t\n153\t  for (const step of config.epicFlow) {\n154\t    const stepStart = Date.now();\n155\t    // Transition epic state before built-in steps\n156\t    const preTransition = STEP_STATE_MAP[step];\n157\t    if (preTransition) {\n158\t      state = transitionEpicState(state, config.epicId, preTransition);\n159\t      config.onStateChange?.(state);\n160\t    }\n161\t    try {\n162\t      await executeStep(step, config, state);\n163\t      stepResults.push({ step, success: true, durationMs: Date.now() - stepStart });\n164\t      stepsCompleted.push(step);\n165\t    } catch (err) {\n166\t      state = transitionEpicState(state, config.epicId, 'failed');\n167\t      config.onStateChange?.(state);\n168\t      return { success: false, epicId: config.epicId, stepsCompleted, stepResults, failedStep: step, error: err.message, durationMs: Date.now() - start };\n169\t    }\n170\t  }\n171\t\n172\t  state = transitionEpicState(state, config.epicId, 'done');\n173\t  config.onStateChange?.(state);\n174\t  return { success: true, epicId: config.epicId, stepsCompleted, stepResults, failedStep: null, error: null, durationMs: Date.now() - start };\n175\t}\n176\t```\n177\t\n178\t**Step-to-state mapping:**\n179\t```typescript\n180\tconst STEP_STATE_MAP: Record<string, EpicLifecycleStatus> = {\n181\t  'merge': 'merging',\n182\t  'validate': 'validating',\n183\t};\n184\t```\n185\t\n186\t**Step dispatch:**\n187\t```typescript\n188\tasync function executeStep(step: string, config: EpicFlowConfig, state: SprintState): Promise<void> {\n189\t  switch (step) {\n190\t    case 'retro': {\n191\t      const telemetry = readTelemetryForEpic(config.epicId, config.projectDir);\n192\t      if (config.dispatchRetro) {\n193\t        await config.dispatchRetro(config.epicId, telemetry);\n194\t      }\n195\t      return;\n196\t    }\n197\t    case 'merge': {\n198\t      const result = await config.worktreeManager.mergeWorktree(\n199\t        config.epicId, config.mergeStrategy, config.testCommand, config.onConflict\n200\t      );\n201\t      if (!result.success) throw new EpicFlowError(`Merge failed: ${result.reason}`);\n202\t      return;\n203\t    }\n204\t    case 'validate': {\n205\t      const result = await validateMerge({\n206\t        testCommand: config.testCommand,\n207\t        cwd: config.projectDir,\n208\t        epicId: config.epicId,\n209\t        writeTelemetry: true,\n210\t      });\n211\t      if (!result.valid) throw new EpicFlowError(`Validation failed: ${result.testResults.failed} test(s) failed`);\n212\t      return;\n213\t    }\n214\t    default:\n215\t      throw new EpicFlowError(`Unknown epic_flow step: \"${step}\"`);\n216\t  }\n217\t}\n218\t```\n219\t\n220\t### Previous Story (19-1) Intelligence\n221\t\n222\t- Story 19-1 created `epic-completion.ts` (~120 lines) — pure logic module with `checkEpicCompletion()`, `transitionEpicState()`, `getEpicStories()`. This story consumes those functions.\n223\t- Testing pattern: vitest, `vi.mock`, colocated tests in `src/lib/__tests__/`.\n224\t- ESM module pattern: `.js` extensions in imports, TypeScript ESM.\n225\t- Build: `npm run build`, Test: `npm test`.\n226\t- All tests passed after 19-1 with zero regressions.\n227\t- State builder helpers exist at `src/lib/__tests__/fixtures/state-builders.ts` — use `buildSprintState`, `buildStoryEntry`, `buildEpicState` for test data construction.\n228\t\n229\t### Git Intelligence\n230\t\n231\tRecent commits (19-1) created the epic completion detection module. This story is the wiring layer on top.\n232\t\n233\tFiles created in story 19-1:\n234\t- `src/lib/epic-completion.ts`\n235\t- `src/lib/__tests__/epic-completion.test.ts`\n236\t\n237\tFiles from epics 17-18 that this story consumes:\n238\t- `src/lib/worktree-manager.ts` (17-1, 18-1)\n239\t- `src/lib/lane-pool.ts` (17-2)\n240\t- `src/lib/cross-worktree-validator.ts` (18-3)\n241\t- `src/lib/merge-agent.ts` (18-2)\n242\t\n243\t### Edge Cases\n244\t\n245\t- **Empty `epicFlow` array**: Return success immediately, transition epic to `done`. No steps to execute.\n246\t- **Unknown step name**: Throw `EpicFlowError` with descriptive message listing the unknown step.\n247\t- **`retro` step with no telemetry**: `readTelemetryForEpic` returns `[]`. The retro callback receives an empty array — the analyst agent can still produce a retro from the sprint state context.\n248\t- **`retro` step with no `dispatchRetro` callback**: Log a message and skip — retro is advisory, not required for epic completion.\n249\t- **`merge` step returns `{ success: false, reason: 'conflict' }`**: Treat as step failure, transition to `failed`, skip validate.\n250\t- **`merge` step returns `{ success: false, reason: 'tests-failed' }`**: Same — step failure, transition to `failed`.\n251\t- **`validate` step fails after merge already cleaned up worktree**: The validate step runs on the main repo (merged result), not the worktree. The worktree is already cleaned up by `mergeWorktree()`.\n252\t- **`transitionEpicState` throws `EpicCompletionError`**: This means the state machine detected an invalid transition. Let it propagate — the executor catches it and marks the epic as `failed`.\n253\t- **Concurrent epic flows**: Each epic flow runs in its own lane. The merge mutex in `worktree-manager.ts` serializes merges. No additional locking needed.\n254\t\n255\t### Boundary: What This Story Does NOT Include\n256\t\n257\t- **Wiring into lane pool scheduling** — The lane pool callback already runs the workflow engine per epic. The epic flow executor is called AFTER the engine finishes all stories. The integration point (calling `executeEpicFlow` from the lane pool callback) is a future wiring task.\n258\t- **TUI display of epic lifecycle** — Epic 20.\n259\t- **Modifying `WorktreeManager`** — It's already complete from epics 17-18.\n260\t- **Modifying `epic-completion.ts`** — It's already complete from 19-1.\n261\t- **Persisting state to disk** — The executor returns updated state. Callers persist via `writeState()`.\n262\t\n263\t### Project Structure Notes\n264\t\n265\t- Source: TypeScript in `src/`, compiled to `dist/`\n266\t- Tests: vitest, colocated in `src/lib/__tests__/`\n267\t- ESM modules — use `.js` extensions in imports\n268\t- Build: `npm run build`, Test: `npm test`\n269\t- The `epic-flow-executor.ts` should be a focused module (~120-180 lines). Orchestration logic with delegation to existing modules.\n270\t- Use state builder helpers from `src/lib/__tests__/fixtures/state-builders.ts` in tests.\n271\t\n272\t### References\n273\t\n274\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/epics-parallel-execution.md#Story 19.2]\n275\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md#Decision 6 -- Epic Completion Detection]\n276\t- [Source: _bmad-output/planning-artifacts/architecture-parallel-execution.md#Decision 4 -- Hierarchical Flow Model]\n277\t- [Source: src/lib/epic-completion.ts]\n278\t- [Source: src/lib/worktree-manager.ts#mergeWorktree]\n279\t- [Source: src/lib/cross-worktree-validator.ts#validateMerge]\n280\t- [Source: src/lib/telemetry-writer.ts#readTelemetryForEpic]\n281\t- [Source: src/lib/lane-pool.ts]\n282\t- [Source: src/lib/hierarchical-flow.ts#BUILTIN_EPIC_FLOW_TASKS]\n283\t- [Source: src/types/state.ts#SprintStateV2]\n284\t\n285\t<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-START:story-verification -->\n286\t## Verification Requirements\n287\t\n288\t- [ ] Showboat proof document created (verification/19-2-epic-flow-execution-proof.md)\n289\t- [ ] All acceptance criteria verified with real-world evidence via docker exec\n290\t- [ ] Test coverage meets target (100%)\n291\t\n292\t## Documentation Requirements\n293\t\n294\t- [ ] Relevant AGENTS.md files updated\n295\t- [ ] Exec-plan created in docs/exec-plans/active/19-2-epic-flow-execution.md\n296\t\n297\t## Testing Requirements\n298\t\n299\t- [ ] Unit tests written for all new/changed code\n300\t- [ ] Coverage target: 100%\n301\t<!-- CODEHARNESS-PATCH-END:story-verification -->\n302\t\n303\t## Dev Agent Record\n304\t\n305\t### Agent Model Used\n306\t\n307\t### Debug Log References\n308\t\n309\t### Completion Notes List\n310\t\n311\t### File List\n312\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_013PuCFdGqfY1KC97FqvkHNR","session_id":"d383a9e0-3bc4-4a94-aaff-6965a5cc223b","uuid":"ee6c5c41-407f-490f-992c-636fb782fc5c","timestamp":"2026-04-03T23:18:33.361Z"}
